## Diagnosis

You're right — this is a recurring pattern where component variants get implemented in source but never reflected in the playground/docs. The playground becomes stale immediately after the first undocumented addition. This is **anti-pattern AP-072: Implementation-Documentation Drift** — the component and its documentation live in separate files with no structural enforcement coupling them together.

---

## Root Cause

The playground page for Navigation is written as a **static, hand-maintained list of examples**. There is no compile-time or lint-time check that asks "does every variant declared in the component's type exist as a rendered example in the playground?" The two artifacts drift silently.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Document the `solid` variant in the playground immediately

**File: `src/app/(playground)/playground/navigation/page.tsx`**

```tsx
// Before (approximate current state):
const APPEARANCE_VARIANTS = ["ghost", "subtle"] as const;

// After:
const APPEARANCE_VARIANTS = [
  "ghost",
  "subtle",
  "solid",          // ← added
] as const satisfies NavigationProps["appearance"][];
```

Add the rendered example in the variant matrix:

```tsx
// Inside your variant showcase section:
<section aria-labelledby="appearance-heading">
  <h2 id="appearance-heading" className="playground-section-title">
    Appearance
  </h2>

  <div className="playground-variant-grid">
    {APPEARANCE_VARIANTS.map((appearance) => (
      <PlaygroundCard
        key={appearance}
        label={appearance}
        // existing props pattern you already use:
      >
        <Navigation
          appearance={appearance}
          items={DEMO_ITEMS}
        />
      </PlaygroundCard>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>
```

The critical line is:

```ts
} as const satisfies NavigationProps["appearance"][];
```

`satisfies` makes TypeScript verify that every string in the array is a **valid member of the union type**. If you add a new variant to `NavigationProps` but forget the playground, nothing breaks yet — see Step 3 for the enforcement half.

---

### Step 2 — Add an exhaustive-variant helper

**File: `src/lib/playground/assert-exhaustive-variants.ts`** *(new file)*

```ts
/**
 * Asserts at the type level that a playground demo array covers
 * every member of a component's variant union.
 *
 * Usage:
 *   assertExhaustiveVariants<NavigationProps["appearance"]>(
 *     APPEARANCE_VARIANTS
 *   );
 *
 * If a new variant is added to the component type but omitted from
 * the playground array, TypeScript raises a compile error — not a
 * runtime warning.
 */
export function assertExhaustiveVariants<TUnion extends string>(
  variants: readonly TUnion[],
): void {
  // Pure type-level check; no runtime cost.
  void variants;
}
```

Use it in every playground page:

```ts
// src/app/(playground)/playground/navigation/page.tsx
import { assertExhaustiveVariants } from "@/lib/playground/assert-exhaustive-variants";
import type { NavigationProps } from "@/components/navigation/Navigation";

const APPEARANCE_VARIANTS = [
  "ghost",
  "subtle",
  "solid",
] as const satisfies NavigationProps["appearance"][];

// 🔒 Compile error if a variant is missing from the array above.
assertExhaustiveVariants<NavigationProps["appearance"]>(APPEARANCE_VARIANTS);
```

---

### Step 3 — Add an ESLint rule to enforce the pattern

**File: `eslint.config.mjs`** (or your existing ESLint config)

```js
// Install first: pnpm add -D eslint-plugin-local-rules
import localRules from "eslint-plugin-local-rules";

export default [
  {
    plugins: { "local-rules": localRules },
    rules: {
      // Enforces that playground pages call assertExhaustiveVariants
      // for each *_VARIANTS constant they declare.
      "local-rules/playground-exhaustive-variants": "error",
    },
    files: ["src/app/**/playground/**/*.tsx"],
  },
];
```

**File: `eslint-local-rules/playground-exhaustive-variants.js`** *(new file)*

```js
/**
 * Enforces that every `*_VARIANTS` const declared in a playground
 * page has a corresponding `assertExhaustiveVariants(...)` call.
 */
module.exports = {
  meta: {
    type: "problem",
    docs: {
      description:
        "Playground pages must call assertExhaustiveVariants for every *_VARIANTS constant.",
    },
    schema: [],
  },
  create(context) {
    const declaredVariantConsts = new Set();
    const assertedVariantConsts = new Set();

    return {
      // Capture: const FOO_VARIANTS = [...] as const satisfies ...
      VariableDeclarator(node) {
        if (
          node.id?.type === "Identifier" &&
          node.id.name.endsWith("_VARIANTS")
        ) {
          declaredVariantConsts.add(node.id.name);
        }
      },

      // Capture: assertExhaustiveVariants(FOO_VARIANTS)
      CallExpression(node) {
        if (
          node.callee?.type === "Identifier" &&
          node.callee.name === "assertExhaustiveVariants" &&
          node.arguments[0]?.type === "Identifier"
        ) {
          assertedVariantConsts.add(node.arguments[0].name);
        }
      },

      "Program:exit"() {
        for (const name of declaredVariantConsts) {
          if (!assertedVariantConsts.has(name)) {
            context.report({
              loc: { line: 1, column: 0 },
              message: `Playground constant "${name}" must have a matching assertExhaustiveVariants(${name}) call.`,
            });
          }
        }
      },
    };
  },
};
```

---

### Step 4 — Add a pre-commit hook as a final backstop

**File: `.husky/pre-commit`**

```sh
#!/bin/sh
# Type-check catches assertExhaustiveVariants mismatches.
pnpm tsc --noEmit
# ESLint catches missing assertExhaustiveVariants calls entirely.
pnpm eslint "src/app/**/playground/**/*.tsx"
```

---

## The Codified Rule

Add this to your `CONTRIBUTING.md` or your design-system ADR log:

---

### Rule DS-001: Variants must be exhaustively documented in the playground

> **When:** Any time a variant prop (appearance, size, intent, etc.) is added, removed, or renamed on a component.
>
> **Required actions (all three):**
> 1. Add the new value to the corresponding `*_VARIANTS` array in the component's playground page.
> 2. The array must be typed `as const satisfies ComponentProps["propName"][]` so TypeScript validates membership.
> 3. The array must be passed to `assertExhaustiveVariants<ComponentProps["propName"]>(ARRAY)` immediately below the declaration.
>
> **Enforcement:** `tsc --noEmit` (CI) + `eslint-local-rules/playground-exhaustive-variants` (lint) + pre-commit hook.
>
> **Rationale:** A playground that doesn't show a variant is indistinguishable from a variant that doesn't exist. Documentation drift is a bug.

---

## Principle

**The playground is a type-level contract, not a prose document.** Structural enforcement (TypeScript `satisfies`, custom ESLint rules, CI gates) must make it *impossible* to ship a variant without a playground example, turning a discipline problem into a tooling problem — which is the only kind of problem that scales.
